The paper deals with the problem of deciding tree t-spanner admissibility of graphs, which involves concepts from graph theory, algorithms, and computational complexity. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), followed by cs.CG (Computational Geometry) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). The paper also presents an efficient dynamic programming algorithm, which suggests the possibility of belonging to cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) or cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-categories.
